XXII - Space, Time and Wisdom
:::

::: {.noteHeading}
Highlight ([orange]{.highlight_orange}) - Location 1841
:::

::: {.noteText}
XXII SPACE, TIME AND WISDOM
:::

::: {.noteHeading}
Highlight ([orange]{.highlight_orange}) - Location 1842
:::

::: {.noteText}
The Western type of consciousness may be said to have begun, as we saw
at the end of Chapter XV, with the emergence of Greek thought from the
Orient.
:::

::: {.noteHeading}
Highlight ([orange]{.highlight_orange}) - Location 1846
:::

::: {.noteText}
Oriental philosophy, hardly distinguishable from oriental theology, is
based, above all, on a determination to regard the sense-world as Maya,
or illusion.
:::

::: {.noteHeading}
Highlight ([orange]{.highlight_orange}) - Location 1849
:::

::: {.noteText}
It is clear, however, that the way of the West lies, not back but
forward; not in withdrawal from the contacts of the senses, but in their
transformation and redemption.
:::

